  Name: Morning Glory
  BotanicalName: Ipomoea nil
  Description: 'Annual or perennial vine, the whole plant has short hairs. Therefore,
    morning glories are generally planted in spring and bloom in summer and autumn.
    They come in many varieties and are common ornamental plants. The fruit is ovoid
    and can be used in medicine.

    Each morning glory flower has only a short
    lifespan of one day, usually blooming in the early morning and gradually closing
    by noon, hence they are also called "Asagao" (morning face).'
  Price: 30
